The mangay‘ is about the size of a cherry- tree, and bears white flowers, which exhale a very delightful odour. It produces fruit of a golden colour, and equal in size to a large plum, which, when ripe, are agreeable to the teste, but hurtful to the stomach. Both the tree and. the fruit overfiow with a kind of milky, and resinous juice, called mangaffci, in the Guarany tongue, which streams out plentifully, when you cut the bark, and is caught by the hand, or by a board. The air curdles it, and gives it the appearance of a little skin. In this state, it is rolled up into balls, which are so remark- ably elastic, that when thrown lightly upon the ground they leap up very high in the air. This liquor, mangaffch is said to be very usesul in cases of dysentery. It is much to be la- mented that so very few take the trouble to collect this rosin, which would be useful in Europe in various ways.
